{"questionId":"20379","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>Two straight fences meet at point <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>A</mtext></math> and a field lies between them.</p>\n<p>A horse is tied to a post, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>P</mtext></math>, by a rope of length <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>r</mi></math> metres. Point <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>D</mtext></math> is on one fence and&nbsp;point <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>E</mtext></math> is on the other, such that <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>PD</mtext><mo>=</mo><mtext>PE</mtext><mo>=</mo><mtext>PA</mtext><mo>=</mo><mi>r</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>D</mtext><mover><mtext>P</mtext><mo>^</mo></mover><mtext>E</mtext><mo>=</mo><mi>θ</mi></math> radians. This is shown in&nbsp;the following diagram.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><img src=\"__IMG__/f1ba8bcdc1e69afbba140214e41b62dca5c09c35.png\"></p>\n<p>The length of the arc <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>DE</mtext></math> shown in the diagram is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>28</mn><mo> </mo><mtext>m</mtext></math>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Show that the area of the field that the horse can reach is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>392</mn><msup><mi>θ</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac><mfenced><mrow><mi>θ</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>sin</mi><mo> </mo><mi>θ</mi></mrow></mfenced></math>.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p>recognising sum of area of sector and area of triangle required&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><msup><mi>r</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mi>θ</mi><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mn>1</mn></mstyle><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mn>2</mn></mstyle></mfrac><mi>r</mi><mo>×</mo><mi>r</mi><mo>×</mo><mi>sin</mi><mfenced><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">π</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>θ</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mfenced><mrow><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msup><mi>r</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo>(</mo><mi>θ</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>sin</mi><mfenced><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">π</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>θ</mi></mrow></mfenced></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>sin</mi><mfenced><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">π</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>θ</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mi>sin</mi><mo> </mo><mi>θ</mi></math>&nbsp;(substitution seen anywhere)&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><msup><mfenced><mfrac><mn>28</mn><mi>θ</mi></mfrac></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup><mi>θ</mi><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><msup><mfenced><mfrac><mn>28</mn><mi>θ</mi></mfrac></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup><mi>sin</mi><mo> </mo><mi>θ</mi></math>&nbsp; OR&nbsp;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><msup><mfenced><mfrac><mn>28</mn><mi>θ</mi></mfrac></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup><mfenced><mrow><mi>θ</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>sin</mi><mo> </mo><mi>θ</mi></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p>area<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo> </mo><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>392</mn><msup><mi>θ</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac><mfenced><mrow><mi>θ</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>sin</mi><mo> </mo><mi>θ</mi></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>AG</strong></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><em><strong>[4 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"20379","referenceCode":"21M.2.SL.TZ1.8b","subjectId":"50-dp-mathematics-analysis-and-approaches","title":"Show that the area of the field that the horse can reach is 392θ2θ+sin θ.","paper":"2","level":"SL","questionNumber":"b","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 4]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 3— Geometry and trigonometry","Topic 3— Geometry and trigonometry","SL 3.2—2d and 3d trig, sine rule, cosine rule, area","Topic 3— Geometry and trigonometry","SL 3.4—Circle: radians, arcs, sectors"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}